    <h2 id="intro">The Mattress Disposal Problem in America</h2>

    <p>Every day, over <strong>50,000 mattresses</strong> are thrown away in the United States. That's roughly <strong>18-20 million mattresses per year</strong> — and fewer than 20% get recycled.</p>

    <p>Here's the problem: mattresses aren't like normal trash.</p>

    <p>The steel springs inside don't compress with other garbage. They create air pockets in landfills, taking up <strong>40 cubic feet of space per mattress</strong> — dramatically more than other household items of similar size. A single mattress takes <strong>80-120 years to decompose</strong>.</p>

    <p>This has become such an issue that cities across the country now charge extra fees for mattress disposal, and four states (California, Connecticut, Rhode Island, and Oregon) have banned mattresses from landfills entirely, requiring recycling instead.</p>

    <p>The good news? <strong>Over 90% of mattress materials can actually be recycled.</strong> The steel becomes construction rebar. The foam becomes carpet padding. The wood becomes mulch. Nothing has to go to waste.</p>

    <p>But most people don't know their options. They either overpay for junk removal, illegally dump their mattress on the curb, or throw away something that could have been recycled — or even donated.</p>

    <p>This guide covers every single option available to you, with real costs, honest pros and cons, and the information you need to make the right choice for your situation.</p>

    <!-- When to Replace -->
    <h2 id="when-to-replace">When to Replace Your Mattress</h2>

    <p>Before we talk about disposal, let's make sure it's actually time.</p>

    <h3>Signs Your Mattress Needs to Go</h3>
    <p>Based on what we've seen from over 1.15 million mattress removals, here's when people typically replace:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Visible sagging or body impressions</strong> that don't bounce back</li>
        <li><strong>Waking up with pain</strong> that goes away during the day</li>
        <li><strong>Sleeping better in hotels</strong> than at home</li>
        <li><strong>Allergies worse at night</strong> despite clean bedding</li>
        <li><strong>You can feel springs</strong> through the surface</li>
        <li><strong>Significant staining or odor</strong> that cleaning doesn't fix</li>
        <li><strong>It's over 7-10 years old</strong> (the average mattress we pick up is about 7 years old)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Why People Get Rid of Mattresses</h3>
    <p>From our experience, the most common reasons are:</p>
    <table class="simple-table">
        <thead>
            <tr><th>Reason</th><th>Percentage</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr><td>Moving (don't want to bring old mattress)</td><td>~35%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Bought a new mattress</td><td>~30%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Spring cleaning / home refresh</td><td>~15%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Estate cleanout (someone passed away)</td><td>~10%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Mattress damaged or worn out</td><td>~10%</td></tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <p><strong>The mattress industry largely follows the housing industry.</strong> When people move, they replace furniture. Tax refund season (February-April) is also peak mattress buying time — which means peak disposal time.</p>

    <div class="info-box">
        <strong>What we've noticed:</strong> Online mattress companies have changed the game. When you buy from Casper, Purple, Nectar, or similar brands, they ship you a new mattress in a box — but they don't take your old one away. That's created a huge increase in people needing standalone mattress removal services.
